	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>West Africa: Regional integration and agricultural trade policy</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 February 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>As part of its Trade Policy Review of Benin, Burkina Faso and Mali, the WTO Secretariat has reviewed the regional agricultural trade policy framework. The primary focus is on the eight-member WAEMU, with a secondary focus on the broader 15-member grouping of ECOWAS.</p><p>According to the WTO Secretariat, WAEMU is committed to the creation of a common market with ‘a common external tariff and a common trade policy’. In this context ‘the majority of trade policy instruments, in practice import measures, have been harmonized at WAEMU level.’ A WAEMU customs union has nominally been in effect since 1 January 2000, including a common external tariff (CET) and harmonisation of VAT and excise duty regulations. However, according to the WTO Secretariat analysis, while a WAEMU CET is applied, there is an ‘absence of harmonization of the import duty exemptions granted by member States’, and as a consequence ‘the tariff protection levels actually granted may vary considerably from one country to another.’ Equally, while in principle ‘agriculture is excluded from the scope of VAT … each member State may choose the VAT regime applicable to the agricultural sector.’ In addition, ‘major tariff and non-tariff barriers continue to hinder intra-community trade.’ For example, the review notes exporters from Burkina Faso and Benin routinely complaining of import bans which prevent movement of a wide range of their food products within ECOWAS.</p><p>While nominally there is free trade in agricultural products within WAEMU, ‘according to several observers this is not really the case and the actual implementation of the legislation remains a challenge.’ Regular questioning of the origin of products is one of the main barriers to trade, with this being ‘compounded by quantitative restrictions, unwarranted controls, long and repetitive formalities at borders’. SPS concerns also represent a significant barrier to trade in the livestock sector, giving rise to a situation where imports from beyond WAEMU are more common than intra-regional trade. Efforts continue to be made to try to eliminate this anomaly in regional trade commitments, including through a variety of trade facilitation programmes.</p><p>In terms of the treatment of food and agricultural products, the average tariff is 14.6%. However, for regionally grown agricultural products the tariff is generally 20%. The WTO Secretariat reports ‘a relatively high level of nominal protection for basic or processed foods’. For agricultural and agro-industrial products, a ‘special import tax (TCI) of 10 per cent may be applied to certain non-WAEMU originating products if their c.i.f. value is below the trigger price.’ The purpose of this tax is ‘to cushion the impact of any sharp fall in world prices on community production and/or offset non-community unfair practices.’ Trigger prices are set ‘on the basis of world prices and average production costs in the member State’, while a different basis is used for ‘products benefiting from guaranteed prices on the United States and European Union markets’. The trigger prices are adjusted every six months.</p><p>With regard to quantitative restrictions and licensing, the WAEMU treaty provides for ‘the phasing out of the quantitative restrictions on intra-community trade’, but the WTO Secretariat notes that ‘no implementing legislation has been adopted for the purpose.’ However, according to the WAEMU Commission, ‘member States do not apply quantitative restrictions in their foreign trade as a whole.’</p><p>The review notes that across the region, ‘poultry breeding farms face strong competition from imports of frozen poultry.’</p><p>In terms of agricultural policy, WAEMU is committed to establishing a common policy framework based on:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘the adaptation of production systems and improvement of the production environment (boosting productivity and competitiveness); </li>

<li>‘deepening the agricultural common market; and</li>

<li>‘integration into the sub-regional and world markets.’</li>

</ul>
<p>Five priority sectors have been identified – rice, livestock and meat, poultry, maize and cotton – and sector master plans were adopted in 2007. Efforts are under way to harmonise SPS regimes within WAEMU, based on mutual recognition, subject to the precautionary principle. Often, however, cooperation in this area awaits transposition into national legislation. WAEMU is also seeking to establish a common regional approach to the use of export levies and taxes as well as common rules on state aid. A common competition policy is also being formulated, but institutional capacity constraints limit the ability of WAEMU to deal with ‘anticompetitive behaviour’. A Regional Agricultural Development Fund has been in place since 2006, but financial resource mobilisation has been limited.</p><p>According to the WTO Secretariat Review, the main policy development in the agriculture sector has been ‘the introduction of subsidies for the production of the main cereal food crops as a result of the food crisis in 2008.’ Government has also been extended to institutional reforms in the cotton sector, where production has been in decline in response to ‘low global prices and poor governance in the subsector’.</p><p>ECOWAS similarly aims to create a free-trade area and customs union among a wider grouping of West African countries. It also seeks to promote a common approach to agricultural policies and establish a common regional agricultural development fund, although this confronts the same problem of financing as the WAEMU initiative.</p><p>Efforts continue to be made to harmonise the WAEMU and ECOWAS processes. However, in January 2008 ECOWAS heads of state and government decided to establish a fifth tariff band ‘at a rate above the highest WAEMU CET rate’. This tariff band was explicitly aimed at protecting agriculture against competition from imports. This ‘fifth band’ is set at 35% and ‘is to apply to a list of “sensitive” goods consisting basically of agri-food products’. However, ‘each member country is responsible for drawing up its own list, which is subsequently to be harmonized with the lists of the other WAEMU countries and then with those of the ECOWAS members in order to arrive at a single common list.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
WTO, ‘Trade Policy Review for Benin, Burkina Faso and Mali’, point of access for all sections of the report, 4-6 October 2010<br/>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp336_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp336_e.htm</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Ensuring the effective application of agreed regional commitments in the context of differing sector priorities and concerns is clearly a challenge for WAEMU. Addressing this challenge is complicated by efforts to harmonise the WAEMU and ECOWAS processes, in the context of the ongoing evolution of ECOWAS tariff policy. The introduction of a fifth tariff band explicitly aimed at protecting agriculture against competition from imports means that agricultural development and food security concerns are at the heart of contentious issues in regional integration processes in West Africa.</p><p>The WTO Trade Policy Review of these countries provides important background to the ongoing West Africa-EU EPA negotiations, in a context where in some agricultural sectors it appears far easier to import from beyond the region than to formally trade within the region.</p>
		</div>
		
